<s docid="FT931-3664" num="4" wdcount="23"> FT 15 MAR 93 / Bombay stays calm in the 
face of horror: The city seems determined to put Friday's outrage behind it</s>

<s docid="FT931-3764" num="6" wdcount="31"> THE INDIAN government flew federal 
paramilitary troops into Bombay last night after more than a dozen bombs 
exploded in the city, killing about 200 people and injuring more than a 
thousand.</s>

<s docid="FT931-2858" num="6" wdcount="24"> The 29-storey Jijobhoy Towers, home of the 
Bombay Stock Exchange, was rocked by two powerful bombs last Friday, leaving 60 
dead and 200 injured.</s>

<s docid="FT931-2858" num="7" wdcount="12"> The market reopened on Monday in an 
attempt to return to normal.</s>

<s docid="FT931-2858" num="9" wdcount="17"> Dealers seemed to like this, the BSE index 
rising by 5.6 per cent on Monday and Tuesday.</s>

<s docid="FT931-2858" num="10" wdcount="23"> But another bomb blast in Calcutta 
triggered nervous selling yesterday, and the index came back by 50.62, or 2.1 
per cent, to 2,409.23.</s>

<s docid="FT931-2858" num="28" wdcount="32"> The Indian stock markets have been 
passing through a series of crises since December, when activists of the 
Bhartiya Janta party pulled down the Babri mosque at Ayodhya, sparking off 
communal riots.</s>

<s docid="FT931-2981" num="16" wdcount="29"> More than 2,000 people died in riots, 
including over 700 in Bombay, after the razing of a mosque at Ayodhya in 
northern India by Hindu zealots on December 6.</s>

<s docid="FT931-2858" num="11" wdcount="44"> All this has taken place against a 
volatile background: the Bombay equity market, over the past six weeks or so, 
has had to contend first with unusually bullish speculation, before the national 
budget on February 27, and subsequently with some savage expressions of 
disappointment.</s>

<s docid="FT931-2858" num="12" wdcount="18"> Dr Manmohan Singh, the Indian finance 
minister, disappointed traders in the budget at the end of last month.</s>

<s docid="FT931-2858" num="16" wdcount="28"> He lowered the tax to 30 per cent from 65 
per cent for expatriate Indians and foreign investors but for local investors it 
remained at 44.5 per cent.</s>

<s docid="FT931-2858" num="20" wdcount="30"> The relative lack of financial 
concessions meant that disappointed traders sold with a vengeance and, until the 
weekend, the market seemed bottomless as equity prices plummeted to a 13-month 
low.</s>

<s docid="FT931-4176" num="8" wdcount="27"> The Sebi has accused stockbrokers of 
flouting the exchange's rules, including regulations on margin trading designed 
to limit the risk of members defaulting through excessive speculative 
investments.</s>

<s docid="FT931-3764" num="12" wdcount="34"> The bombs appeared designed to stir a 
renewal of communal strife and to undermine efforts by the government of Mr PV 
Narasimha Rao to open up the economy and attract foreign investment and 
tourism.</s>

<s docid="FT931-3664" num="38" wdcount="27"> But much more should go to the people of 
Bombay, who, so far at least, have refused to be goaded into violent protest by 
the bombers .</s>
</SUM>
